"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141057","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-25","<p>In December 2018, we announced £2 million funding for National Health Service trusts in England to install Changing Places facilities in hospitals and significantly improve provision. From 31 May 2019, NHS trusts can bid for this funding, on a matched basis.</p><p>We are supportive of the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government consultation which ran from 12 May 2019 to 22 July 2019 and sought views on how to increase provision of Changing Places toilets in specific new, large buildings commonly used by the public, as well as those undergoing building works. They propose to introduce a mandatory requirement for Changing Places in Building Regulations for some specific new, large buildings.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-07-25T14:21:03.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141057/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141057/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-22","Public Lavatories: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to increase the number of changing places toilets with hoist and a bench throughout the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","280137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141058","Department for Education","false","2019-08-02","<p>The government recognises the importance of digital skills to employability and participation in society. To help tackle digital exclusion, from 2020, we will fully fund adults with no or low digital skills to undertake new improved digital qualifications free of charge. These will be based on new national standards which set out the digital skills people need to get on in life and work.</p><p>In the interim, we will continue to support the provision of basic digital skills training for adults in colleges and community learning settings through the Adult Education Budget and other programmes.</p><p>With regard to requesting leave for training or study, an employee can request time off if they have worked for their employer for at least 26 weeks, if the training will support them in their job role, and if the organisation they work for has at least 250 staff.</p>","Saffron Walden","Mrs Kemi Badenoch",,"2019-08-02T12:06:03.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141058/answer","Biography information for Mrs Kemi Badenoch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141058/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141058/answer/previousversion/131203","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","60","Education","Education","2019-07-22","Lifelong Education: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he has taken to introduce (a) a right to lifelong learning in digital skills and (b) a right for all employees to request leave for training.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","280308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141059","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-24","<p>We have committed to protecting leaseholders who are suffering at the hands of rogue managing agents every day from unexpected costs or excessive fees for poor quality repairs.</p><p>We set up a working group, chaired by Lord Best, to look at regulating and professionalising property agents. This included reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents. The working group has now completed their considerations and made recommendations to ministers. The working group’s final report was published on 18 July.</p><p>The Government will consider the recommendations set out in the report and will respond in due course</p><p>We are also looking at the future use of charges and restrictions beyond service charges – such as permission fees, administration charges and other restrictions and covenants faced by leaseholders and resident freeholders, and consider whether they should be capped or banned, and will consider this alongside the working group’s proposals.</p><p>The Government has committed to ensuring that residential freeholders who pay charges for the maintenance of communal areas and facilities on a private or mixed tenure estate can access equivalent rights to those of leaseholders to challenge their reasonableness. This will include a right to change the provider of maintenance services by applying to the tribunal for the appointment of a new manager.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","280310 ; 280311 ; 280312","2019-07-24T16:45:55.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141059/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141059/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Owner Occupation: Service Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to protect freeholders and leaseholders from high service charges.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141060","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-24","<p>We have committed to protecting leaseholders who are suffering at the hands of rogue managing agents every day from unexpected costs or excessive fees for poor quality repairs.</p><p>We set up a working group, chaired by Lord Best, to look at regulating and professionalising property agents. This included reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents. The working group has now completed their considerations and made recommendations to ministers. The working group’s final report was published on 18 July.</p><p>The Government will consider the recommendations set out in the report and will respond in due course</p><p>We are also looking at the future use of charges and restrictions beyond service charges – such as permission fees, administration charges and other restrictions and covenants faced by leaseholders and resident freeholders, and consider whether they should be capped or banned, and will consider this alongside the working group’s proposals.</p><p>The Government has committed to ensuring that residential freeholders who pay charges for the maintenance of communal areas and facilities on a private or mixed tenure estate can access equivalent rights to those of leaseholders to challenge their reasonableness. This will include a right to change the provider of maintenance services by applying to the tribunal for the appointment of a new manager.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","280309 ; 280311 ; 280312","2019-07-24T16:45:55.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141060/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141060/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Owner Occupation: Service Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to tackle uncapped service charges on freeholders and leaseholders.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141061","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-24","<p>We have committed to protecting leaseholders who are suffering at the hands of rogue managing agents every day from unexpected costs or excessive fees for poor quality repairs.</p><p>We set up a working group, chaired by Lord Best, to look at regulating and professionalising property agents. This included reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents. The working group has now completed their considerations and made recommendations to ministers. The working group’s final report was published on 18 July.</p><p>The Government will consider the recommendations set out in the report and will respond in due course</p><p>We are also looking at the future use of charges and restrictions beyond service charges – such as permission fees, administration charges and other restrictions and covenants faced by leaseholders and resident freeholders, and consider whether they should be capped or banned, and will consider this alongside the working group’s proposals.</p><p>The Government has committed to ensuring that residential freeholders who pay charges for the maintenance of communal areas and facilities on a private or mixed tenure estate can access equivalent rights to those of leaseholders to challenge their reasonableness. This will include a right to change the provider of maintenance services by applying to the tribunal for the appointment of a new manager.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","280309 ; 280310 ; 280312","2019-07-24T16:45:55.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141061/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141061/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Service Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to ensure accountability and transparency in service charges.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141062","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-24","<p>We have committed to protecting leaseholders who are suffering at the hands of rogue managing agents every day from unexpected costs or excessive fees for poor quality repairs.</p><p>We set up a working group, chaired by Lord Best, to look at regulating and professionalising property agents. This included reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents. The working group has now completed their considerations and made recommendations to ministers. The working group’s final report was published on 18 July.</p><p>The Government will consider the recommendations set out in the report and will respond in due course</p><p>We are also looking at the future use of charges and restrictions beyond service charges – such as permission fees, administration charges and other restrictions and covenants faced by leaseholders and resident freeholders, and consider whether they should be capped or banned, and will consider this alongside the working group’s proposals.</p><p>The Government has committed to ensuring that residential freeholders who pay charges for the maintenance of communal areas and facilities on a private or mixed tenure estate can access equivalent rights to those of leaseholders to challenge their reasonableness. This will include a right to change the provider of maintenance services by applying to the tribunal for the appointment of a new manager.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","280309 ; 280310 ; 280311","2019-07-24T16:45:55.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141062/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141062/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Owner Occupation: Service Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to ensure fairness between freeholders and leaseholders on challenging high service charges.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141063","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-24","<p>Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL) and section 106 contributions can be used to provide and maintain roads and other infrastructure. Our recent reforms enable local authorities to hold developers to account when infrastructure is provided as part of new development. Where developers do not deliver on contributions, this can be enforced through legal proceedings.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-24T16:30:26.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141063/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141063/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Roads: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that developers are accountable to local authorities when appointing sub-contractors to build roads and other infrastructure; and what powers local authorities have to ensure that developers contribute adequately to the cost of maintaining roads once adopted by the local authority.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141064","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-24","<p>The Secretary of State made his decision to implement the Northamptonshire councils’ unitary proposal with one modification. This modification was to extend the period for implementing the new arrangements so the new councils are operational from 1 April 2021. We took this step to ensure a successful transition to the two new unitary authorities and that there would be confidence locally about a safe and effective transition to all the new service delivery arrangements across the whole of the area, including for those crucial services supporting the most vulnerable.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-07-24T15:30:15.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141064/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141064/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Unitary Councils: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to (a) ensure that local authorities in Northamptonshire transition successfully to the two new unitary authorities on time and on budget and (b) prepare for the proposed new unitary authorities not being operational on time and on budget.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141065","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-25","<p>Provision of Adult Social Care is a Government priority, which is why this Government has given councils access to £10 billion dedicated funding that can be used for adult social care in the three year period to 2019-20.</p><p>Government has continued to subsidise the supply of new supported and sheltered housing as well as investing more than £2.7 billion into the Disabled Facilities Grant (DFG) between 2012-13 and 2019-20. The DFG has been funded through the Better Care Fund since 2015 in in recognition of the crucial role which home adaptations can play in supporting the integration of housing, health and social care.</p><p>The Department has also strengthened the revised National Planning Policy Framework so that local planning authorities are expected to have policies which identify the size, type and tenure of homes required for different groups in the community.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-25T09:16:30.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141065/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141065/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-22","Housing: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of including adult social care provision within housing development plans.","false","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","280315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141067","Department for Education","false","2019-07-29","<p>Teaching Vacancies is a free job listing service for schools to list teacher vacancies. A phased roll out commenced in September 2018 with the official national launch in April 2019. To date, 60% of schools have signed up to use the service.</p><p>The Teaching Vacancies website is available here: <a href="https://teaching-vacancies.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://teaching-vacancies.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-07-29T15:49:51.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141067/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141067/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141067/answer/previousversion/131236","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","60","Education","Education","2019-07-22","Schools: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to provide a single jobs portal for all schools to advertise vacancies.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","280317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141068","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-26","<p>The latest available data on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) registrations, clearances (whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) and claims in payment can be found on Stat-Xplore at: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. This data can be broken down by region and by month.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-26T10:39:59.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141068/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141068/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-22","Personal Independence Payment: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of people who claimed personal independence payment in Wales in each year since its inception.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","280163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141069","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-30","<p>We have made no such assessment. UK law enforcement agencies maintain regular engagement with the Hong Kong Police Force in the course of information exchange and joint investigations of serious and organised crime – as they do with counterparts throughout the world. All cooperation with overseas partners – including those in Hong Kong – is conducted under the Overseas Security and Justice Assistance (OSJA) risk management system.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-30T13:33:20.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141069/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141069/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-22","Hong Kong: Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the integrity of the Hong Kong police service.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","280212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141070","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-02","<p>Statistics surrounding the volume of Universal Credit claims is routinely published and can be found on the Department’s Stat-Xplore service: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a>/. Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p />","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-09-02T14:36:29.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141070/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141070/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-22","Universal Credit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of people who have claimed universal credit in Wales in each year since its inception.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","280164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141071","Department for Education","false","2019-08-02","<p>The department is keen to make the system easier to navigate for young people considering taking technical and vocational routes and has therefore conducted extensive research with over 2,000 young people, colleges and career advisers. While the research indicated that young people would value a central source of information as they make decisions about their next steps, it did not show that they found the application process itself challenging.</p><p>As a result, the department is focusing first on ensuring young people have the right information on all of their options, including on technical education and apprenticeships. The department is redeveloping the National Careers Service website, including the post-16 course directory, and our careers strategy sets out our plans for improving the careers provision that young people receive in school or college.</p><p>The department is still considering the feasibility and practicality of a centralised portal for further education and will make final decisions on this in the context of wider reforms to technical qualifications.</p>","Saffron Walden","Mrs Kemi Badenoch",,"2019-08-02T12:55:24.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141071/answer","Biography information for Mrs Kemi Badenoch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141071/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141071/answer/previousversion/131206","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","60","Education","Education","2019-07-22","Vocational Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he has taken to introduce a UCAS-style portal for technical education.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","280318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141072","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-30","<p>The violence we have seen in Hong Kong is unacceptable. We should not speculate on the identity of violent groups until a thorough investigation has taken place. We welcome Carrie Lam’s statement on 22 July saying she has asked the Commissioner of Police to investigate the incident at Yuen Long MTR station fully and pursue the lawbreakers.</p><p>We also note the announcement of a special inquiry by the Independent Police Complaints Council into recent events in Hong Kong. We look forward to the publication of further details about the scope and composition of the investigation.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-30T13:35:49.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141072/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141072/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-22","Hong Kong: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his counterpart in Hong Kong on potential collaboration between Hong Kong police and organised crime groups in response to recent protests.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","280319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141073","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-30","<p>It is unlawful for Taxi and PHV drivers to refuse to carry passengers accompanied by assistance dogs and it is unacceptable that a minority continue to discriminate in this way. The Government’s response to the Task and Finish Group on Taxi and PHV licensing committed to introduce legislation when time allows to require drivers to complete disability awareness training as part of national minimum standards. The eventual requirement and supporting guidance will be informed by public consultation and appropriate research.</p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","280321","2019-07-30T11:19:42.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141073/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141073/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-22","Taxis: Assistance Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for conducting and publishing research on why taxi and PHV drivers continue to refuse to transport assistance dogs.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","280320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141074","Cabinet Office","false","2019-07-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","280166","2019-07-25T10:38:20.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141074/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141074/answer","Combined PQ280165 and 280166.pdf","Combined PQ280165 and 280166.pdf","UKSA Response","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141074/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-07-22","Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of people employed by local authorities in England in (a) 2010 and (b) 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","280165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141075","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-30","<p>It is unlawful for Taxi and PHV drivers to refuse to carry passengers accompanied by assistance dogs and it is unacceptable that a minority continue to discriminate in this way. The Government’s response to the Task and Finish Group on Taxi and PHV licensing committed to introduce legislation when time allows to require drivers to complete disability awareness training as part of national minimum standards. The eventual requirement and supporting guidance will be informed by public consultation and appropriate research.</p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","280320","2019-07-30T11:19:42.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141075/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141075/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-22","Taxis: Assistance Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for carrying out and publishing a consultation on revised best practice guidance to support local licensing authorities to use their powers more effectively when dealing with Taxi and PHV drivers refusing to transport assistance dogs.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","280321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141076","Cabinet Office","false","2019-07-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","280165","2019-07-25T10:38:20.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141076/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141076/answer","Combined PQ280165 and 280166.pdf","Combined PQ280165 and 280166.pdf","UKSA Response","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141076/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-07-22","Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many local authorities in England have reduced their total workforce by (a) 500-999 employees, (b) 1,000-1,999 employees and (c) over 2,000 employees since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","280166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141077","Department for Education","false","2019-08-08","<p>As at 23 July 2019, there are six independent schools sponsoring a total of 13 academies. All of these independent schools were approved as sponsors prior to 2017.</p><p>Of the free schools we have opened since 2017, the London Academy of Excellence (LAE) in Tottenham was set up by an independent school, Highgate School. LAE Tottenham is supported by Highgate School, as well as eight other leading independent partner schools.</p><p>The school’s sister school, LAE Stratford, was set up by Brighton College in 2012. The school reported that in the 2018/19 academic year, 26 students received offers from Oxford or Cambridge. This is an outstanding achievement, especially in a geographic area with relatively low Oxbridge destinations.</p><p>The Department has a joint understanding with the Independent Schools Council to encourage more independent schools to work in partnership with state-funded schools across four key areas: governance, teaching, curriculum and targeted school improvement. The Department announced funding for cross-sector partnerships in June and will invite bids in the autumn.</p><p>The joint understanding also encourages independent schools to offer a greater number of full bursary places, targeted at children from disadvantaged backgrounds.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-08-08T16:23:44.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141077/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141077/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141077/answer/previousversion/131225","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","60","Education","Education","2019-07-22","Schools: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education,how many independent schools have become involved in academy sponsorship or the founding of free schools in the state system since 2017.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","280322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141078","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-07-31","<p>The Government has not made such a specific assessment though we do consider the distributional impact of our interventions on different groups, including low income households, in our adaptation planning.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/climate-change-second-national-adaptation-programme-2018-to-2023" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/climate-change-second-national-adaptation-programme-2018-to-2023</a></p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-07-31T13:16:29.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141078/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141078/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-07-22","Climate Change: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of climate change on social and economic inequality in the UK.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","280167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141079","Department for International Trade","false","2019-07-31","<p>The Government ministers who will attend the Defence and Security Equipment International 2019 event have not yet been confirmed.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-07-31T12:32:33.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141079/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141079/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-07-22","Arms Trade: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which Cabinet colleagues will attend the Defence and Security Equipment International 2019 event.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","280323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141080","Department for International Trade","false","2019-07-31","<p>The Government provides a range of support to Defence and Security Equipment International (DSEI), including the provision of military assets and engagement by Government Ministers. The Department for International Trade’s Defence and Security Organisation invites a number of international delegates on behalf of Her Majesty’s Government including overseas ministers, senior Government officials and military staff. All invitations to overseas delegations follow a stringent process of scrutiny and approval involving both the Department for International Trade and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-07-31T16:24:30.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141080/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141080/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-07-22","Arms Trade: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what support the Government is providing to the Defence and Security Equipment International 2019; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","280324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141081","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-07-29","<p>Published totals by local authority for 2018/19 and 2019/20 are not yet available. Data for 2018/19 will be published at YOT level in the annual statistics published in early 2020. Data for 2019/20 will be available one year later.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","280326","2019-07-29T15:19:40.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141081/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1141081/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-07-22","Youth Justice Board: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the value of the Youth Justice Board grant to each local authority was in 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","280325"
